<br>
But pretty much, since Kunark, Verant had a vision of SK and Pal being the &quot;defensive tank&quot;  along with Warriors where as Rangers Rogues and Monks are the &quot;offensive tank&quot;.  This concept actually sounds great on paper, HOWEVER, the way Verant worked it out doesn't work at all.<br>
<br>
Here's the problem.<br>
<br>
Pre-Kunark<br>
<br>
Defensive tank is:<br>
1)Plate class<br>
2)Higher Hp<br>
<br>
Offensive tank is:<br>
1)Double attack<br>
2)Dual Wield<br>
<br>
<br>
Pretty much, the only think that sets makes Rangers more offensive than a pal/sk is the ability to dual wield which they sacrifice the ability to wear plate for.  And of course Rogues gets backstab and a few special &quot;evade&quot; abilities and monks get higher skills to make up for their lesser armor etc.<br>
<br>
This works out pretty well maybe with the exception of Monks being slightly powerful but you can more or less replace one of the following class of the same catagory with another depending on what you're looking for.  <br>
<br>
But of course, class specific armor broadened the gap.<br>
<br>
In Kunark, Verant made it so Pure melees has significantly higher skill than Hybrids at first which pretty much  made hybrids into crap so I don't need to go into that.<br>
<br>
But of course they attempted to them by giving the &quot;defensive hybrid&quot; same def cap as warriors and &quot;offensive hybrid&quot; same offensive skill cap.  Again, the idea works on paper but in actuality, it doesn't.<br>
<br>
First of all, the entire concept of a &quot;defensive hybrid&quot; doesn't really work. With the now popular, class specific armor, the AC gap between a similar level equipped warrior and pal/sk can goto upwards of 150.  And the hp gap can go up to over 1000hp.  This will lead to my second point..<br>
<br>
At high end game, Verant introduced mobs meleeing upwards towards the range of 1000+ and then some.  This more of less means that in order to tank the mob, you need absolutely the highest hp/ac possible character to tank them.  Also, to tank a mob, it means that at any given point and time, the mob will ONLY be able to melee 1 target at a time (rampage doesn't count because you're not actually tanking the target damage and can easily be avoided by standing out of range).  Mobs only having one target at a time means defense DOES NOT stack!  So in order to be as efficient as possible, its the best idea to have the highest ac/hp ppl tank the mob.  <br>
<br>
On the other hand, offense DOES stack.  It means at any given point and time, multiple people can melee a mob.  So rangers actually are significantly more attractive to &quot;uber guilds&quot; than a pal/sk.  Also, with a lot of the newer boss mobs such as Dain, Tunare, and nut sack sized character bind box of Yelinak, there can only be a limited amount of melees to be engaging the mobs, so it is less attractive to have lesser melees taking up space.<br>
<br>
Also, at the same time, with newer Velious equipment, Monks and Rogues can have similar or very close within a couple hunder hp and few ac within that of a Pal/SK.  It means that a Monk/Rogue and out damage a Pal/SK significantly while tank just as well.  <br>
<br>
All in all it means that SK/Pal are pretty much screwed.<br>
<br>
Warriors are the ONLY tanks.<br>
<br>
Rogue and Monks are superior to SK/Pal and every way<br>
<br>
Rangers aren't really that bad because they can actually dish out damage.<br>
<br>
That's pretty much it...<br>
<br>
Of course as hybrids we get Spells!!!  woooo.. more crap..  versatility = crap!  Oh yah and LoH... it heals half the hp of a fully buffed warrior... big fuckin' whoop right there!<br>
<br>
Guess that's enough ranting... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
